I start escitalopram depression medication in the coming days. 

I know it won’t fix everything but I do now believe it will give me a more stable baseline to feel.

It took for my wife and mum to intervene and tell me that’s it’s ok to not want to keep battling on. In fact it’s actually necessary. It’s ok to need a different solution. At some point you have to accept. I need it to stop.

I’ve always just assumed that it’s the norm to just feel low, to have extreme thoughts, to find everything taxing, unreal high to unreal low. I tried everything, I really went for it, I like that I battled so bard but I think the real battle has been accepting it for what it is.

I’ve asked myself countless times why I feel what I feel. I’ve got so much in terms of support and love and security. But ive realised something I’d never thought about before. Its not about any of that… it’s deeper, it’s in the brian.. It’s depression.

Worst has been the fact that I’ve spent about 10 years being aware of something being majorly up. All focus on trying to ‘fix me’, trying really really really hard to help myself through, I’m jokes proud of that… that makes me feel.

Not drinking, drinking, extreme diets, extreme temperatures, extreme coffee, special plants, more sleep, more running, eternal kindness, therapy, walks in deep woods, and openly(ish) talking about it more visibly.

I’ve tried so many ways in which to make myself feel less aware of being aware of the constant jumping from one fix to the next in hope of staying on the right side of feeling completely lost and emotionally tired.

The mind is amazing. Mad to think that it’s so complex that you can miss signs. I now feel more consciously aware of the existence of depression. It’s not even a thing or a non thing, it’s something and it’s ok to admit it.
